o-Bejarano contributes to the development of a language to talk about sexuality as potentially empowering, the place of desire within politics, and the intricate workings of racialized desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLesbians in literature. 0aMexican American women in literature. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and literature--United States--History--20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/79607240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292759879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292759879/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK